Let `Œ∫ : kernel Œ± (Œ≥ √ó Œ≤)` and `ŒΩ : kernel Œ± Œ≥` be two finite kernels with `kernel.fst Œ∫ ‚â§ ŒΩ`, where `Œ≥` has a countably generated œÉ-algebra (true in particular for standard Borel spaces).
We build a function `f : Œ± ‚Üí Œ≥ ‚Üí Set Œ≤ ‚Üí ‚Ñù` jointly measurable in the first two arguments such that for all `a : Œ±` and all measurable sets `s : Set Œ≤` and `A : Set Œ≥`, `‚à´ x in A, f a x s ‚àÇ(ŒΩ a) = (Œ∫ a (A √óÀ¢ s)).toReal`.

```suggestion ```

The interest of beta and `s : Set beta` is not clear to me in this construction -- since you're fixing s, I have the impression that this construction is equivalent to a construction without \beta, i.e., with two \gamma-valued kernels.
Indeed, since you're fixing the set `s`, couldn't you just evaluate the kernel on `t \times s` to get a gamma-valued kernel, and then you would habe two gamma-valued kernels \kappa' and \nu with \kappa' \le \nu.

Maybe it's important in applications to have the additional beta? Could you comment on that in the file-level docstring? In particular, I see that you have several lemmas describing what happens when a sequence of sets `s m` increases to `univ` or decreases to emptyset, this is probably relevant but currently not mentioned at all in the file-level docstring.

I have two applications of that code, one for which beta is important and one for which it isn't:
- for kernel disintegration, I want to take `Œ∫ : kernel Œ± (Œ≥ √ó Œ≤)` and write it as a composition-product of `fst Œ∫` and a `kernel (Œ± √ó Œ≥) Œ≤`. I will go through beta=R with sets `s` taken to be `Iic q` for rational `q`, and build a kernel by a kernel cdf construction, hence the monotone sequences of sets.
- for the Radon-Nikodym theorem for kernels I don't need beta and will drop it.

I'll add a paragraph about the uses of the `density` construction and explain that there.
I don't understand the naming `_I`. Also, doesn't the finiteness assumption on kappa follow from `hŒ∫ŒΩ` (here and below)?

It seems a little bit far-fetched to use a pi-system argument in such a simple situation. Do you have the fact that any set measurable wrt `countableFiltration Œ≥ n` is a finite union of atoms? From this, the conclusion would be direct from `set_integral_densityProcess_I`, without the need for ` integral_densityProcess`.

```suggestion
    (hs_meas : ‚àÄ m, MeasurableSet (s m)) :
```
(keep `n` for the index of the countable partition). Same thing below several times.

```suggestion
lemma memL1_limitProcess_densityProcess (hŒ∫ŒΩ : fst Œ∫ ‚â§ ŒΩ) [IsFiniteKernel Œ∫] [IsFiniteKernel ŒΩ]
```
The naming of this lemma (and of the following ones) is a little bit too generic, as it does not indicate you are considering a specific situation. Add `fst` somewhere, here and below?

```suggestion
  rw [integral_iUnion, iUnion_prod_const, measure_iUnion,
      ENNReal.tsum_toReal_eq (fun _ ‚Ü¶ measure_ne_top _ _)]
  ¬∑ congr with u
    rw [set_integral_densityProcess_of_mem hŒ∫ŒΩ _ _ hs (hS_subset (by simp))]
  ¬∑ intro u v huv
    simp only [Finset.coe_sort_coe, Set.disjoint_prod, disjoint_self, bot_eq_empty]
    exact Or.inl (h_disj huv)
  ¬∑ exact fun _ ‚Ü¶ (measurableSet_countablePartition n (hS_subset (by simp))).prod hs
```
You can combine the `rw` to get one indentation level less.
